    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-08-04T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-08-04T15:00:00-05:00" n="94"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d94">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/116</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">London</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-04T20:00:00+00:00">
                        <hi rend="italic">August 4, 1914, 8 p.m.</hi>
                    </date>
                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 11:10 p.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                <p>263. The Counselor of the German Embassy has informed Mr.
                        <persName>Laughlin</persName> that the German Ambassador will give Germany’s
                    answer to England’s ultimatum to-morrow and that he expects to leave London on
                    Thursday morning, when the German Embassy will be turned over to me.</p>
                <p>The German Naval Attaché has just told Commander Symington that he regards war
                    with England as certain and that he has so telegraphed his Government. He
                    remarked that every hour that Germany could now gain was of very great value and
                    that for this reason Germany might temporize with England somewhat.</p>
                <p>The Austrian Ambassador called on me this morning and made all arrangements to
                    turn over his Embassy to me, expressing his expectation to leave London very
                    soon.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
